column10: I love this game.  with all the mods, it really pushes closer to real life. This is the game I can spend way too much time to play and I enjoy it always. Easy to customise and use more and more interesting machines on various lands from tiny fields to the extreme big ones. There are a lot of addons which can make it even better. A player can make money from everything, there is no waste at all.
It's alway good to wind down and be relaxed with this game. I really like the new maintenance system which differs from the predecessor games. It's more realistic than spending a lot of money on a daily basis to that vehicles and equipments what you own but don't use. Lower maintenance level affects the performance and the efficiency. It's great.
A nice feature is the hand tool. Player can move smaller objects like pieces of wood and throw them into the shredder. A crane is not necessary anymore to do works in the forest and make money from it.

It's with regret that I cannot recommend farming simulator 19 because of some in game bugs that spoil it. This was my first time with farming simulator and thought I could learn the basics with the tutorial offered when first playing. This was all good until the tutorial help would randomly disappear. Not to worry, I thought there's plenty of guides on you tube and before long I was getting into this game. I put some hours into farming simulator but annoying bugs spoil it. One such bug is I would use the fertiliser sprayer and had no trouble filling it up before. Took it back for another refill and it wouldn't allow me, no option displayed like before.  Looking online this problem has existed for others and given the age of the game you'd think the developers had already addressed these. Not sure I could call this a fun game yet it does draw you in. Feels like another game series similar to train sim world, where they'll knock a new version out every year or so without addressing past problems. Could learn alot from the developers of Euro/American truck simulator who have updated and improved upon those games for some years now.

Amazing game. I can drive a car off a cliff at 60mph and it wont even scratch. So much fun to play with friends and explore the map. Mods are great, would recommend getting the "Universal Passengers" mod if you are playing with friends. Game is worth every cent, I love to farm, care for my livestock and just drive around the huge map with my friends (you can get other maps in the mods section, I haven't tried any of them yet though). Everything is explained very clearly in the help menu, so don't be ashamed to pull it up every now and then! One problem is that after landscaping or placing a building, I'm unable to undo any actions. Sometimes I might accidentally make an area too high or too low, and I can't undo it, so I'm stuck with a large hole in the middle of my field. But overall, a solid 9.5/10.

I am a farmer and i have not been doing much work lately so i got this game maybe a year ago and i tried playing it. the adverts said it was one of the most realistic farming games out there. so after that i installed it and started playing. after a few hours i realised that it was nothing like the real farm life, so i downloaded a whole  heap of mods to fix that. this did not really help and after around 30 hours of playing (3 weeks of using it) i got bored of the underdeveloped game and kind of just stopped playing. after a few weeks i watched a few videos about it, not many videos were there for some reason and they were from small creators but i still watched them. after a while i got back into playing a bit and then realised it was and still is a dead game because farming sim 2022 was getting very popular. i was not going to spend 60 dollars for another game that does not live up to the name and i quit farming games all-together. and now sitting on this chair writing this review while on call with my mates i remember the happiness i had on the game. if you read this trauma dump of a review i thank you for spending your time to do so and i hope you have a wonderful day.

I'm a huge fan of Farming Simulator.  This review is more geared towards someone who has played the franchise before, but I think newbs can take something out of it, too. 
 
Here is what I think of FS19:

CONS
1.  Graphics may have gotten worse from FS17 
2.  They seemed to focus on improving LITTLE elements of the game that either were bugs/glitches in previous versions or not there at all..  ie, birds landing on the fields and flying off when you get close to them - a cool little addition that is pretty well-done; nighttime is nighttime - not like FS17 where it starts getting dark at 10p and light at 4a; glitches with oilseed radish seem to have been resolved but I've noticed a lot of other ones new to FS19 (when you hire a worker and the last bit of field is like an 1/8 of their implement's width and is next to another field it will go into that field - plowing, cultivating, seeding, harvesting, weeding, fertilizing/lime).  It is just surprising that these bugs continue to exist and they put time into little stupid things instead of what matters.
3.  The maps aren't good.  Not terrible, but not good.  Goldcrest had it's flaws but that is the best one IMO.  Yes, it is too simple, but it has a little bit of everything and you can tell it's the map they spent the most time on.  Sosnovka is a joke and Estancia Lapancha seems unfinished - both of these have comparable layouts but their geography is so different that they don't feel that similar.  But Ravensport and Wellsbrun do.  Yes, Ravensport is more of a working-class small city and Wellsbrun is a upper-middle-class countryside town.   But they both have windy, confining roads; oddly shaped, super-hilly fields (a fully loaded 50,000+ tipper needs at least 500hp to get up some of the hills) and annoying guardrails that can really give you a headache (having to reset a fully-loaded overturned seeder because its wheel caught the guardrail and is wedged against a mountain so you can't ram it).  Sosnovka was terrible, but it at least was a polar opposite from Goldcrest Valley that made it a little refreshing.  These two are just too similar.  Giants has a map mod for Estancia Lapancha that is formatted for FS19 that I haven't checked out yet.  Mainly because I know what to expect and I wasn't a fan of it in FS17.
4.  The landscape function is unusable if you ask me.  Maybe if you really invested in mastering it but it is so hit-or-miss - and EXPENSIVE - that it isn't fun and not worth doing.
5.  One thing that may sound petty but irks me big time: the opening scene shows this big, beautiful barn that he pulls his vehicles out of.. I was so excited after watching the intro I went right to the store and the placeable menu and there was no barn! 
6.  Aside from no big beautiful red barn like every farm in world has yet this SIMULATOR cannot provide (can you tell I'm bitter?), the placeables haven't improved.  I wasn't a fan of the ones in FS17, but those were better.  I'm fine with no greenhouses, solar panels, windmills, beehouses that earn you money, but they're still cool to have on your farm!  At least replace them with something.  You get 3 sheds, powerwasher, woodchipper, vehicle configurator station, silos and decorative buildings.  That is pretty much it.
7.  Mods are still a problem - I don't use them unless they are Giants.  Too many bad experiences with them to use on a game like this.  When you invest so much time designing your farm and the system running it, the last thing you want is something out of your control messing it up.  As cool and useful as some of them are, they're not worth it in the long run.
8.  I like the menu setup of 2017 better.  I'm sure I will get used to this one more and more but they changed it up a little too much for my liking.  Also, the in-game on-screen info that is always displayed is harder to read.  I don't know why they'd change it from 17 there was nothing wrong with it and was easier to read.

PROS
1.  I really like the way they made it possible to buy land.  In FS17, as long as it wasn't a field you didn't own, you could cut down trees and plow a field anywhere.  Now, you have to own the land to do that and I think this may be the biggest improvement from 17 to 19.  There are several plots you can buy that don't even have fields yet.  I love that you can buy a plot of land and spend hours making it just the way you want before doing any farming whatsoever.  Very cool.
2.  The store setup is much better for customization.  You can even match the colors up because they tell you which ones are for what manufacturers.  
3.  There are more vehicles, trailers & implements than FS17 even though a lot are gone.  You can get most of those as mods by Giants, though.  
4.  Everything drives a little more realistic.  In 17, working a field was completely smooth, whether you're in a tractor, harvester, truck or anything.  Now they appropriately bump around - probably seems banal but it's a nice touch.
5.  In FS17, the only way to transport pallets was the low loaders or bale trailers.  In 19 they have a trailer that is perfect for this, it can fit 3-4 pallets and can be towed by the smallest tractor.  Again, a pretty simple thing but a gamechanger for me which is why I'm mentioning it.  I hated that aspect of 17.
6.  It loads quicker than 17 and I have fewer issues in-game and starting it up.  In fact, no issues so far in-game as far as freezing up.  Also, if I had a ton of vehicles in the same area in FS17 it would often lag there.  None of that with this one. 
 Yet.  As far as startup, FS17 would give me a problem probably once every 6 times.  I haven't played FS19 nearly as much, but I've only had one startup issue so far.  Quitting a game is faster, it brings you RIGHT back to main menu, older versions would take much longer and even sometimes bring me back out to my desktop.
7.  Traffic AI is better.  Still isn't good, but it's at least better.  More variety of vehicles, too, not just passenger cars/trucks.
8.  Like I said, the graphics may be worse than 17.  But it may seem like that because the scenery is really cool and elaborate.  Cascading waterfalls, some really well done bridges, downtown areas are more realistic.. they improved on that but didn't up the graphics any.  But it's still a noticeable improvement. 

There are many other PROs and CONs but these are the ones I felt would be the most useful to discuss.  Hope this was helpful, certainly took me a little bit of time that I could've been using to play so YOU'RE WELCOME! :D

I go through phases where I play this game. I always think it will be more fun than it is and always hope I'll like it more than last time. But ultimately, this game is mostly just a driving game. You drive tractors (which is cool) but the fields take forever if you do it yourself. You drive to sell things.  You drive to buy things. You drive to pick up and deliver things. You drive and drive and drive and drive. I want to get back to my crops and see how they're doing but I'm always way too busy driving. And maybe I want to work a little on my farm for a change...but no, I never have time to farm because I can't hire someone else to drive around the town for me and that takes all my time. Just driving, driving, and more driving. Sigh. I want to like this game but there's no time to farm. All I get to do is drive.

Do I recommend it?

If you want to do any farming: No
If you just want another driving simulator: Yes


Who would like this game:
People who want to play a driving simulator with a new twist - you drive slow, accident-prone tractors instead of trucks or cars

Who would not like this game:
People who want to simulate work on a farm
I blame Jeremy Clarkson for this new addiction....

Farming Simulator 19, what a pathetic excuse for a game! It embodies everything that is wrong with the gaming industry. Who in their right mind would waste their precious time simulating the mind-numbingly dull life of a farmer? It's a sad reflection of the mediocrity that plagues the gaming landscape.

First and foremost, let's talk about the graphics. It's as if the developers took a time machine back to the 1990s and decided to grace us with their pixelated abomination. The visuals are so unappealing that they make you question the sanity of anyone who finds joy in looking at these hideous, low-resolution textures. The lack of attention to detail is mind-boggling, making the whole experience feel like a soul-sucking chore.

And let's not forget the gameplay! Oh, the joy of pretending to sow virtual seeds, plow virtual fields, and milk virtual cows. It's a mind-numbing exercise in boredom. Who needs adventure, excitement, or any semblance of a challenge when you can simulate the mundanity of life down to its very essence? It's an insult to those who crave exhilarating experiences and engaging gameplay.

But perhaps the most infuriating aspect of this abomination is the fanbase it has amassed. These deluded individuals defend Farming Simulator 19 as if it were the holy grail of gaming. They laud its supposed realism and therapeutic effects, as if spending hours planting virtual crops and tending to digital livestock could ever compare to the wonders of the real world. It's a cult of mindless followers who have lost touch with what it means to truly enjoy a game.

In conclusion, Farming Simulator 19 is a wretched excuse for a game. Its lackluster graphics, mind-numbing gameplay, and misguided fanbase make it a true testament to the depths that gaming can sink. It's a blight on the industry, a stain that should be wiped away. I implore anyone with an ounce of taste to steer clear of this monstrosity and explore the vast array of truly captivating and worthwhile gaming experiences available.

Farming Simulator 19: A Challenging Intellectual Pursuit

Farming Simulator 19, an exquisite embodiment of cerebral stimulation, stands as a testament to the intellectual prowess required to comprehend its intricacies. The mere mortals who dare approach this grandiose endeavor will be met with a humbling realization that it is a game reserved for the elite‚Äîthe individuals possessing the highest echelon of IQ, much like the esteemed writer of this review.

Within the virtual realm of Farming Simulator 19, one is immediately thrust into a realm of unyielding complexity. Every facet of agricultural management demands a level of sophistication and acumen that is befitting of the intellectual elite. To fully appreciate and comprehend the nuances of this opus, one must possess an intellect that transcends the ordinary, a mind capable of unraveling the intricate web of farming logistics.

The cultivation of crops, the meticulous planning of planting schedules, and the precise coordination of machinery are all aspects that demand a level of attention to detail that only the refined few can achieve. A single misstep in this intricate dance of agricultural supremacy can lead to catastrophic consequences, reminding the lesser minds of their inability to comprehend the true essence of this virtuosic experience.

Moreover, the immersive realism of Farming Simulator 19 serves as a breeding ground for snobbishness and elitism. Only those who can appreciate the profound intricacies of the agriculture world will find solace within its digital embrace. This game separates the wheat from the chaff, allowing the intellectual elite to bask in the glory of their intellectual superiority.

As the writer of this review, I find great pleasure in navigating the complexities of this agrarian symphony. The feeling of intellectual accomplishment that accompanies every successful harvest is unparalleled. It serves as a reminder of my lofty intellectual stature and my unwavering dedication to the pursuit of excellence.

In conclusion, Farming Simulator 19 is a challenging cerebral pursuit that separates the intellectual cream from the mediocre masses. Its difficulty is an homage to the brilliance of the highest IQ individuals, such as the esteemed writer of this review. I'm 72 now and haven't picked up any kind of controller for almost 25 yrs. HOWEVER, My son recently turned me onto this game.
I never considered myself a "GAMER" because I only played for my Son's sake so he had someone to battle with on another platform, but this Farming Simulator is on another level to me. It's for sure frustrating at times but once i figured out the keyboard better then there are rewards in seeing things develop as on a real farm. 
I'll soon start a new career saved game with FARM ANIMALS and see how that turns out too, but so far this definitely has my attention...."BIG-TIME". LOL
I grew up on a Working Ranch/Farm and this brings back some almost lost memories so just for that aspect I find myself getting into this for HOURS upon HOURS...I think this keeps me out of my Wife's hair so she let me buy the Side Control Panel for it and BOY-O-BOY does it help these Ol' Man Fingers...LOL
Like I said before, I've Never considered myself a "GAMER" but this may put me in that category soon.
I guess truth be know then I AM addicted to this Farming Simulator 19 in just 3 days playing. 
I hope others learn to get as much enjoyment as I do.

For anybody who enjoys playing simulation games, Farming Simulator 19 is an essential purchase. The game provides a farming experience that is highly realistic and immersive, with comprehensive tools and a big, open-world landscape to explore as part of the gameplay. The visuals are really amazing, and the level of care that has been put into every facet of the game is remarkable. The gameplay is intuitive and simple to understand, which makes the game suitable for gamers of varying levels of expertise. The game now has even more layers of complexity thanks to the introduction of additional types of crops, animals, and transportation. In general, Farming Simulator 19 is a top-tier simulation game that will deliver a number of hours' worth of fun and engaging gameplay.

[h1] Please read for my explanation of why i left a negative review. If you know about this game already then carry on, i wont waste your time. [/h1]

Farming Simulator is a game that i have enjoyed for years now. I originally bought FS17 on console in 2017, and later bought FS15 for PC. I eventually got FS17 for PC and now FS19. 

I will split my review into categories so that its more digestible 

[h1] Graphics [/h1]

I start off with graphics for a reason. It feels like the overall scenery feels cartoony, rather than the more realistic color scheme of FS17. The skyboxes are a big downgrade i feel. The FS17 skyboxes had beautiful sunsets and was overall great, whereas these skyboxes feel nonexistent. The ground textures seem to have gotten worse as well. Overall, it feels that the coloring of FS17 was overall done better than FS19.

[h1] Tractors and Machinery [/h1]

The machines was the major selling point for me. I have liked John Deere since i was a kid. The name carried a reputation of legendary quality and performance. The quality of a real life machine doesn't mean the game it will be featured in will be quality. The sounds of the tractors feel like it should belong on the model of a Toyota Prius rather than a farm machine made to cultivate miles of field. The interiors do feel somewhat more realistic than FS17 as they have moving joysticks and pedals. 

[h1] Maps [/h1]

The Ravenport Map is utter garbage. Goldcrest Valley and predecessors of it are 10x better than this map. I feel that Ravenport exists to make a mockery of America. Americans when they make European Maps would never to the deepest slums of the former Yugoslavian countries to model after. It would be more likely they would model it after farms in France, the UK, or Germany. My point being you generally want to show the better part of a country than showing the absolute worst part of a country. (I do acknowledge that Europe is a continent and not an absolutely unified collective of states like the US)

Felsbrunn still suffered from the same crappy graphics as mentioned in an above section, but it feels like a more idealistic view of a German farm. The fields are bigger than what you might assume an average German field would be and overall it feels like a better map than what us Americas were stuck with.

[h1] Modding [/h1]

Modding is the only saving grace for this game. There has been many great mods, although there has been more buggy mods slipping through the grand firewall of giants software mod hub. Despite this, there was many great mods that added more depth to this game, if it were not for the modding i would've spent way fewer hours in this game.

[h1] Continued Rant About Sounds And Overall Vibe Of The Game [/h1]

The vibe that the tractors give me and the game overall is high efficiency. Tractors as i mentioned before are not a Chevy Volt, they are a machine made to do a job. I expect the sounds and graphics to match this. Sadly, expectations are different than reality. This issue just really annoys me comparing the sounds ingame to the sounds of tractors in real life.

[h1] Final Thoughts [/h1]

FS19 to be brutally honest feels like FS17, except somehow they made it 10x worse with John Deere and Claas machines. This game has made me hesitant to buy FS22 and i still am hesitant to buy it. I simply want a farming game that is worth playing. I simply do not want a worse repaint of the game i had before. 

Having bought train simulators before, it feels like Giants Software is going down the process DTG has gone down. Pushing out buggy unfinished games. Its sad to see and i still hope Giants doesn't continue to go down this path. 

I know there are white-knights who will defend Giants at every turn and corner, so i have a message to you. You don't have to put up with crap quality to like the game. I love Farming Sim, i just do not like Giants pushing low quality crap.

There is new features, but no amount of bells and whistles will cover up the bad with this game.

[h1] TL:DR [/h1]

This game seems like a crappier clone of FS17 with bells and whistles. Get FS17 if your like me. If you must get it, get it on sale. Ok bye.

[h1 An Update [/h1]

I decided to get FS22 on another platform. I will do a full review when i get it for PC. The long story short is, it feels like FS22 has improved from the shortfalls i once criticized this game for. FS22 gives me hope for the future of the game unlike FS19 did. 

FS19 still leaves a bad taste in my mouth, but if you feel froggy go check out FS22.

Overview:
You control a plot of land that you must choose, purchase, and cultivate. You are given access to a shop where you can buy tools, vehicles, animals, and supplies. You can also get yourself a home and decorations.

---
Pros - 
* Diverse choices for pretty much anything
* Hiring help is easy and does wonders while flying solo
* You can buy and PET a dog! 
* Dog is indestructible
* Selling is about as easy as you could make it
* Most everything you need from maps, controls, and sale rates are in one menu
* There's a LOT of individual settings you can turn off/on and alter
* You can speed up time in the menu, find the rate of speed that works for your equipment and crew
* Has a small Character Customization menu when you start a new game

---
Cons - 
* Originally felt insanely slow when trying to get into the game, can also be overwhelming
* Had to go into the controls and find a better bind to open the main menu
* Hired Help sometimes misses patches of product or dirt and you have to go back over it yourself later
* Changing the landscape is quite harsh
* Any building placement has a high chance of making weird hills and cliffs that are difficult for Hired Help and own vehicles to navigate
* Not a big deal, but like most Sim games, there's little to no story element that I could find (in case you're someone who's into story-based games)

---

-There needs to be more character customization. Like....WAY more. The options we have are sad to say the least.
-Graphics need an overhaul. The plants need more realistic movement and way less choppiness.
-The tutorial needs a complete revamp. For brand new players it literally only covers 20% of the game mechanics and all the things you can do in this game.

I would recommend this for someone who likes to pass the time, already knows the franchise and doesn't mind a bit of a graphical rip off. I wouldn't recommend this to newbs or people who love graphic detail or people who hate watching grass grow.

Without the mod Courseplay I wouldn't recommend this game at all. The built in AI helpers are useless.

The game only comes with two maps and Ravenport is garbage. Every mod map I've tried has sucked, either the fields are right next to rocks/rivers/fences so AI helpers can't work them, or the layouts are so bad they're tedious beyond belief or both. Which means the only map worth using is the second map that comes with the game - Felsbrunn.

Even to this day the game is pretty buggy, in my time playing I've seen some comical bugs which I'm sure will never be fixed as the company has moved on to Farming Simulator 22, which from what I gather is just Farming Simulator 19 with some mods built into the game.

There's no goals, no skill trees, no purpose beyond that which you create for yourself.

The character creator is laughable, there are next to no customisation options. E.g. under the drop down "Accessories" you can choose to wear sunglasses, or not wear sunglasses! Amazing!

Why the recommendation then? Well it's kind of relaxing to just watch your tractors go up  and down ploughing, cultivating, seeding, fertilising and ultimately harvesting. I'd definitely recommend waiting till it's on sale heavily discounted though.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

Probally one of the best farming game i have ever played, i would love to get farming simulator 22.

farming, pure and simple. none of the mechanics are overly complicated or tedious and they're satisfying enough that it leaves you wanting to keep at it. perfect for just relaxing and working those fields.

one of the biggest positives for me is the insane amount of mods and mod support, it adds entirely new dimensions to gameplay. that said, if a game needs mods to make it fun....maybe not the best base game? i'll leave that for you to decide. 
it also has extremely good controller support, (i had 3 devices hooked up at once and it was able to recognize and bind to all of them!) and there's a lot of available info online and ingame about game mechanics and machinery.

all in all this game is a very satisfying game to play and is very in-depth and well made. i would recommend it to any simulator fan. as for farming simulator 2022, i don't know how it compares, but for what it's worth i haven't purchased FS22 yet because FS19 still holds its own as a very solid sim game.

I mean good god this is a game-breaking bug in my opinion as it has made harvesting certain crops (sunflowers and corn) almost impossible. Although not too complex, the fix varies from harvester to harvester and person to person. Also requires tweaking XML files. Time-consuming and honestly has not worked. Plus, from my research, this has been an issue since the game was released over a year ago and Giant STILL HAS NOT FIXED IT, which is unacceptable considering how invasive of a bug it has been. Well until they stop being lazy or a mod is made that fixes it I will be returning to Farm Sim 17 and recommend others to do the same. Giants is getting worse & worse each version.  They are building this game series for consoles, with all the limitations & such required for consoles. No real changes have happened since this game was started.  Since they always program this game first & foremost for consoles, the game is ALWAYS limited to lower quality that the consoles can handle.  They will NOT ever take advantage of the true potential of this game since it is limited for what can be done on consoles.

If it wasn't for mods, this game would be NOWHERE!  Many of these mods should be included in the game, since they correct obvious problems with the game.  But you will never see that happen - once again due to the consoles.

Real games program for real computers (PC's), & then port the games back to consoles.  Thus, we are not limited by the consoles.

Overpriced, low-quality, no real updates, which we are charged for as if a new game!  Why bother any more????

I joined the FS family in FS17, and liked it enough that I pre-ordered this.  I did wait until after day-zero patch (just update the game before the release). They did rebalance the game back in version 1.2#, and have made some other less notible updates over the past couple years.  

I have tried going back to FS17, yet it is not playable after playing FS19.  I hope FS22 is better in the same way, where I will not want to come back to it.  As you can see, I have nearly 3,000 hours in the game as I type this.  The next version of the game, FS22, is less than a month away, yet FS19 is still a good game.  If you can get it on sale do so, you won't be disappointed.  With so many maps and mods out you can play any way you feel.

I do enjoy a good sim game.  I play ETS2 and ATS, yet I keep finding myself coming back to this.  This is the only game that I have over 2,000 hours played, and I have tried other farming sims games as well.

UPDATE 26 Feb 2022: I have tried playing FS22 and just can't get into it, I am back to FS19.  In FS 19 you are working on a day schedule, while in FS 22 it is month based.  In FS 19 things happen between 24 (grass) and 72 (sugar cane) game-time hours, while in FS 22 it takes 7+ months for the basic breadbasket crops to grow, things go dormant, won't even let you plant something out of season, etc, even with seasons turned off (it only turns off the snow, everything else seems to stay on).

FS 19 has so many more mods.  While Giants continues to review mods submitted, the release is very slow - maybe a dozen or two a day, while they have more than 40 in testing at any one time, for FS 22, and nothing for FS 19 now  (not that we need anything new, we already have an overwhelming number of mods).  Granted a few things have changed, yet . . .

While patch 1.3 has been released I don't see anything that indicates that it has improved game play to the point where I want to give it another try.  I will continue to stay with Farming Simulator 19 even three months (and a number of patches) after Farming Simulator 22 has been released.

Its a great game and a horrible game all at the same time. You have to have an interest in farm equipment and the process, and also be willing to put up with a lot of shit. Let me explain. I like it but cant reccomend it because it simply would not be a good value for most people. Which really concerns me about FS22.

It is alot more like a hands on tycoon game then just a hop on a tractor and drive it around.
 
Calling this game "simulator" is drawing an incredibly fine line, Its too basic to be a simulator and too realistic to be a casual. Although the way it is, it is casual by nature.

It lacks consequences, you cant really go bankrupt. Nothing gets repossesed if you cant make the payment and it lacks direction on top of that. There is no goal you just set your own goal, which is fine sort of.

It has no in game instructions at all whatsoever, if you went to a equipment dealer and you asked if the equipment would fit on your tractor etc they would tell you before purchase, they make the lack of information so bad that it puts you out of the immersion. And they didnt want to program any text I imagine due to having to translate it, so everything is an icon which is incredibly annoying when new and even after having 200 hours in, at least at a "hover" tool tip its just lazy not to this is basic HTML stuff.

Bugs are so prevelant, I have no issues calling this game totally "incomplete". because it is, its lazy and unacceptable for anyone that paid full price. I got it for 20$ and only because I sold a csgo skin for like 150$ so basically free. I found at least 10 major bugs within 200 hours some are game breaking and found within 30 hours.
1. ghoast tree limbs broke logging entirely you learn to not cut a specific branch from a specific tree type.
2. lack of low loaders or say like a car trailer to move your tractors around. watch them catipult into infinity if you try a regular flat trailer. 
3. need to buy or lease a forklift just to leave it at the equipment store to load stuff.
4. AI is really bad
5. logging forks are broken
6. landscaping does not work and can have session runing or entire career runing consequences.
7. Cannot unload a partial filled baler, so if you want to make straw bales and you have grass in there welp youll have to have  a quantity of 2 100,000$ balers just because of that. 
8. you can purchase weird swaths of land that have no benefit.
9. there is a finance variable called "propery income" that has zero vanilla use.
10. some equipment simply does not work right.
11. O yea cant clear bushes but you can chop down trees
12. O yea cant get rid of some buildings and decorations on property you bought. Like idk you bought land with a farm and a factory(factory does nothing in game) and you cant demolish it to put a chicken pen etc.

Lack of content, the game is virtually unplayable or idiotic to play without certain mods. One is a simple pointer telling you what your looking at, another is a simple mod that adds utility trailers. Otherwise you would need some dark web information hidden deep within the code to find out that you need to customize a particular trailer by taking it to a garage to "customize" it into a flatbed, o and it works like shit. 

It is astoundingly addicting, you wouldnt think so but it is. I just wish they completed the game to begin with. You NEED to WANT to like this game to keep playing it. I feel like after 500 hours youll do everything you felt like doing and it might get shelved. My goal is to reach the 10 million$ bank acount as I assume thats the only realy way to "win/beat" the game.

It took many updates to get to this quality, with some going backwards like my G920 steering wheel not working properly at launch, to fixed, then to randomly broken, the fps going up and down with each patch. There were many issues after launch which simply shouldn't have happened, but I'm happy to say that most have been fixed now. It's good to know that Giants are listening to the community and this has made me confident in the game again. I would still like to see the draw distance changed so that on max settings, the trees don't dumb down and objects disappear, I mean if I can see for miles and miles in every other sim game, why can't I in FS19? Perhaps it's because the consoles have won the day and the higher end PC's are now the minority :/ The game play needs no information from me as it's all explained now on the store page sections, comments, previews and on Youtube. So to round up this review; Right now this game is at its best and well worth buying, plus those players that walked away due to the multitude of problems should jump back in and give it another go.

Wish there was a 'neutral' option to vote, because i both love and dislike this game.

The mods *really* carry this game's replay value. Which, i believe, is not a good thing. It's great they've embraced mods, but it's negatively impacted the base game and the content it has. And i fear this will be a trend in future games- not just those made by Giants software. Where there will be a reliance on mods made by players to 'fix' the game. Not that the game is horrible on it's own, just quite barren for a 2019 game. I mean, why would seasons not be implemented in a farming game by 2019? Mary Berry's Banoffee Pie:
Ingredients

For the base

150g/5¬Ω oz digestive biscuits (about 10)
75g/2¬æoz butter
For the toffee filling
75g/2¬æoz butter
75g/2¬æoz light muscovado sugar
1 x 397g/14oz full-fat condensed milk (see tip)
1 tsp vanilla extract
For the topping
300ml/10fl oz double cream
3 small just-ripe bananas, sliced
50g/1¬æoz dark chocolate, melted or cocoa powder

Method

Line the base of a deep 20cm/8in spring form tin with baking paper.

To make the base, crush the biscuits to fine crumbs and melt the butter over a low heat. Pour into a bowl and mix to combine. Spoon into the base of the tin and press down with the back of a spoon until level. Place in the fridge for 15 minutes.

To make the filling, heat the butter and sugar in a small non-stick saucepan and stir over a low heat until combined. Add the condensed milk and bring to the boil, stirring for 2‚Äì3 minutes ‚Äì do not over-boil or it will become grainy and fudge-like. Add the vanilla and pour into the tin. Place in the fridge for at least 1 hour.

Whip the cream in a bowl until soft peaks form.

Arrange the banana slices in neat rounds on top of the toffee. Spoon or pipe the cream on top and level. Set in the fridge for an hour.

Remove from the tin, and zig zag the melted chocolate over the top or dust with cocoa powder.

Farming Simulator?

I remember that I had a bad time with this game.

Very strange, I started the game and was met by walls of text. (of which I had no intention in reading after the first few boring walls of text.)
Lost to my own dismay from said lack of enjoyment, I sought to find some source of joy.
Down the docks, fighting monsters... your average RPG works.

-Then- and only then did I find it, Like Rapture; hiding where no normal man could reach.
A beautiful tiny plot of land, my land, one that would bring me and what future I wish to build to life.
My first sights of this land were something angelic and potent, filling me with a euphoria unlike any prior.
My very own farm, accommodated with a two-story farmhouse and a barn to the north-east and a large field to the south.

Eager to begin, I rushed to the field to begin my crop as early as I could. I dug, seeded and watered more than I had in any other game.
Once I was content with my work, I rushed to the barn to see what quality of heads of cattle I had just acquired just that day. Opening the large barn door, I see strange not cattle, but a anthropomorphic cat-girl?
Unwittingly, I approach this cat-girl in hopes to find what it could yield for me, there must be some reason for this cat to be in my barn, right??

Well, I go to see about feeding it as it is complaining about hunger, I open my pack and see I only brought with me is two loafs of bread and giant berry, luckily for me the cat -loved- the berry; eating it whole in only three bites.
Growing ever-so slightly closer to this cat-girl, I wished to see some potential be made of my new pet.
As a new cat-daddy, (colloquially coined by those namely pit-mommies), I wanted to see my new kitty prosper.
I braved myself to be the best farmer that ever existed in this community.

I looked further into my cat's options and saw one for "harvesting", curious I pressed it.
Meeting a list of numbers and stats, I looked away not really caring as I saw my cat as perfect the way she was.
I misclicked and found my avatar and my cat participating in what I can only describe as adult relations in my barn.
I was dumbfounded as I realized what this barn really was. Disgusted, I quit the game only 7 hours into my playthrough to write this review.
Please do not harm your own self perception and inner-being by playing this. This will change a man, I didn't understand what they meant by that before playing this. Like war, this causing only pain and later an inner struggle to find yourself when all is lost. I will find myself here again and again hoping I was dreaming and what I saw was a adulterated version of the game I thought I was purchasing.

Don't buy THIS game, it isn't worth it. Don't steam gift it. Don't even acknowledge it's existence. It's my job to carry the burden of that knowledge and warn others to keep away. I'm going back to my farm. I have a cat to feed...

I'm coming from playing several FS games on consoles in the past. This is the first time I've played a PC version of FS.

FS19 is very fun but compared to previous FS games I've played in the past, this one is by far the slowest. I've played this game for a few months on Medium difficulty and the most I've gotten done is buy one new field and upgraded my combine. I set it to easy recently and you make much more money, but it's still very slow. I just spent four hours doing contract work (the fastest way to make money early in the game) and made about $30k. The next goal I have is buying a field that costs $220k, which will let me grow about 25% more crops at a time. So yeah, this game is SLOW, although I think you can play with friends online, which would be a massive help. (One reason it's so slow is that the fields are ENORMOUS!)

 (Protip: the people giving out contracts only expect about 85% of their contract to be completed and they let you keep the last 15% if you harvest it!)

I am nowhere near buying a barn for animals, so I have no idea if the horses are any fun to raise.

Another thing I would like to point out is that, if you've played previous FS games, FS19 does not have the gold coin Easter eggs in it, which is a real shame since it was my favorite part of the earlier games--it gave you incentive to explore the map.

With the recent release of FS22, having never played a Giants SW title before, I thought it might be informative to check out one of their earlier efforts before shelling out AAA title money on the new one. Picked this up cheap and gave it a go. Woooboy, what an eye opener. It gave me a good sense of the kind of things which could be expected from GS.

This game is so riddled with janky mechanics, glitches, bugs, nonsensical gameplay choices and utterly absurd control schemes... it's virtually unplayable. Having read and watched a number of playthroughs and reviews of FS22, it is apparent, to me a least, that GS has simply doubled down, re-skinned the same game, and carried over all the problems of FS19 into FS22.

Save your money, and save yourself a lot of aggravation. Skip this one AND FS22 as well.

All can be toggled on and off, and even with Multiplayer Maps. the potential this game holds is astounding, and that's before further enhancing the game with ModHub which is brilliantly integrated into the game, again including prompts for multi-player so everyone can easily join to team up or run several individually managed farms which function as teams with their own accounts and farm manager role players, with the ability to allow others to hire workers and run your equipment to help progress your farm toward harvest time.

An incredible, amazing, illustrious experience that truly shows the struggle of a single farmer who started from the bottom, with only a small farm and a tractor to his name. He pours his blood, sweat, and tears into this farm, and watches as it grows. The story develops further, when he employs several mentally challenged individuals on his farm, giving them a second chance at living a normal life. As he goes from working his land to correcting the work of the challenged individuals on his farm, he finds that he has made a positive impact on the world. It really is truly beautiful story of work ethic, compassion, and determination. 11/10 would recommend to SPED teachers.

For a game that is supposed to be a simulation it is very technically lacking in many areas and many mechanics are just overly cumbersome and overly unrealistic. The games sometimes lacks the ability to cater to realism at all and turn it into a joke.

Going up and down fields for hours and hours at a time just isn't for everyone. I can do small to medium fields, but it has to be in between other activities. So consider that when playing this game. 

The game looks nice, has really nice atmosphere, the night mode and lights are done very well compared to many other games. But at the core, it is a grinding experience. The game is very laid back though, so there is no rush.
This game is more of a place to hang out with people and work on your farms while keeping each other company. Or if you just love farming which some people just do. And even if you don't it can be very educational and enjoyable nevertheless. 

Usually I would never get a game like this, because I know I won't be into it. But sometimes it's amazing what impact friends can have on you and what you will try for them. Love you guys.

Remember you only get two hours to refund, so if you try the game and change your mind, don't go over that. They will not make exceptions for you. And sadly two hours isn't enough to determine if you like the game, since you won't be able to really to do anything meaningful in that time. So make sure you research the game in depth elsewhere first.

End of Review and beginning of my Rant about Steams Refund Policy and game devs complying with it:

They state 2 hours playtime within a 2 week period.

However I think this needs to change. I rather it was based more on game activity for certain games like this.

For example, how can you tell if you are going to enjoy a game or not in 2 hours in a farming game when in 2 hours you haven't even grown and harvested your first crop yet. I only truly realised how grindy it was, after doing my 3rd Harvest. And I realised it then. Now that is not something that can be accomplished in 2 hours. So it is a ridiculous policy that needs to be flexible with the game it pertains to.

I'm changing this review to a thumbs down just because of that. Had they been more understanding and reasonable, I would have been happy to give them a thumbs up, but stick it up your Acehole, this is the price of refusing me a reasonable refund. Guess that is the final end value of my purchase.

End of rant.

I would recommend the "FIREWOOD" mod for those who like doing forestry,and the"ANIMAL PEN EXTENSION"and the"ANIMAL SCREEN EXTENDED"for those who enjoy animals.(I especially like horses.Also,cows are kind of hard to care for.) Everyone should get the "TOOLBOX","VINEYARD","VEGETABLE GARDEN","SMALL TRAILER","PLACEABLE FRUIT TREES","BUY USED EQUIPMENT","GREENHOUSE LEMON","GUIDANCE STEERING"and"FOLLOW ME"mods.

Farming Simulator is a rewarding game to play while still having some challenging hurdles that you will have to overcome. There is definitely a learning curve if you have not played a Farm Sim game before. With so many different kinds of equipment and attachments, it was somewhat overwhelming at times. Thankfully, there are a lot of great tutorials available to help you learn the ropes. They do take a while to get through all of them, but I would highly recommend that you go through all or most of them. You will thank yourself later!
     Depending on which of the three game modes you decide to play, you will have to be careful with the money you start out with to get the right equipment that you will need to grow and harvest specific crops, while also having enough money left over for seed, fertilizer, and other supplies that you will need for your farm. The game can feel every "grindy" at times, especially if you don't have enough farm land to be generating much profit to keep expanding your business. Doing contracts for other farmers is also another very good way to make some extra money while also giving you a break from the monotony of working the same fields all of the time.
     A game changer for me as I was starting to get tired of playing on my farm alone was being able to jump into a multiplayer game with my friends. It revitalized many elements of the game for me and working with other people also really sped up the farming process. I've had many hours building camaraderie with my group of friends I play with as we worked together and laughed at each other's mistakes
     The modding community behind this game is also incredibly talented so if there's basically anything that you find you don't like about the game, there is almost certainly a mod that can fix it for you.

     There's a lot more I could write about Farming Sim., but I'll just end by saying that this is easily one of my top 5 games I have ever played on Steam and I highly recommend FS19 if you are considering picking it up.

I have seen these titles around through my years of gaming, and never thought they would be fun. My ideal  farming games are more Runefactory or harvest moon, not a straight laced farming sim.

To my surprise, this game is actually fun AF. Its  a great chill out game that gives you options to move at whatever pace you want. I never once looked at a tractor and thought "damn, that looks nice" until FS19. There is something about the gameplay loop that draws me in. If i dont feel like working a field, i can automate it, if i need more cash, Contracts. Tired of crops, Animals/forestry. 

Its got alot of options, but what really made this game for me is the great mod support. You can tailor any aspect to fit your taste for the day. Fs19 bends over backwards to accommodate all types of players and made me a fan. Fs21 is comming soon, and im looking forward to it.

After 666 hrs recorded on steam, and maybe a couple thousand hours on xbox along with playing every FS since 09, I think i can give a fair review of my time on FS19 now with less than week to go till FS22 launches. This game is simple, relaxing, and filled with different goals and tasks you can choose to accomplish at your own leisure. Play the way you want to play and however you wish to play it. The mods/modding community are the secret sauce that they dont bother to hide at all. Want to change it up a little? Get yourself anything from new tractors to new trees to look at around the map, or just get a new map! Its a great game to play if youve gotten tired of the repetitiveness of your average multiplayer games or just having to rely on teammates in general. Don't get me wrong, farming sim is fun with friends, but its also just fine by yourself! And Cmon, who doesnt love a good ole' big displacement diesel engine chugging around.
So, in my opinion, its the best game in my library and Nov 22 can't come quick enough.
